{"title_page": "Southern Illinois Salukis football", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName         = Southern Illinois Salukis football\n| CurrentSeason    = 2020 Southern Illinois Salukis football team\n| Image            = Southern Illinois Salukis logo.svg\n| ImageSize        = 250\n| HeadCoach        = [[Nick Hill]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 3rd\n| HCWins           = 10 <!-- As of games through 2018 season -->\n| HCLosses         = 23 <!-- As of games through 2018 season -->\n| Stadium          = [[Saluki Stadium]]\n| StadCapacity     = 15,000\n| StadSurface      = [[FieldTurf]]\n| Location         = [[Carbondale, Illinois]]\n| Conference       = [[Missouri Valley Football Conference|Missouri Valley]]\n| FirstYear        = {{Start date|1905}}\n| WebsiteName      = SIU Salukis Football\n| WebsiteURL       = http://siusalukis.com/sports/m-footbl/silu-m-footbl-body.html\n| ATWins           = 412\n| ATLosses         = 477\n| ATTies           = 32\n| BowlWins         = \n| BowlLosses       = \n| BowlTies         = \n| NatlTitles       = 1 (1983)\n| ConfTitles       = 8\n| Heismans         =\n| AllAmericans     =\n}}\n\nThe '''Southern Illinois Salukis football team''' represents [[Southern Illinois University Carbondale]] in [[American football|football]]. The Salukis are a member of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and compete at the [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[Football Championship Subdivision]] level (formerly known as NCAA Division I-AA). The Salukis are a member of the [[Missouri Valley Football Conference]] and play in [[Saluki Stadium]] on the campus of Southern Illinois University Carbondale in [[Carbondale, Illinois]], which has a [[seating capacity]] of 15,000.\n\nThe Salukis are coached by [[Nick Hill]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Hefferman|first=Todd|work=[[The Southern Illinoisan]]|url=http://thesouthern.com/news/hill-to-succeed-lennon-as-siu-s-next-football-coach/article_ac4738ba-eebe-5724-946c-e467a8ac78f4.html|title=Hill to succeed Lennon as SIU's next football coach|date=December 23, 2015|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref> who was the starting quarterback for the Salukis in 2006 and 2007.\n\n== History ==\n{{Expand section|date=January 2011}}\nIn 2006, the Salukis defeated [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana University]] in [[Bloomington, Indiana]], 35\u201328,<ref>{{cite web|website=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=262590084|title=Hill tosses 4 TDs as I-AA Salukis shock Indiana|date=September 16, 2006|accessdate=January 12, 2011}}</ref> becoming the first [[Missouri Valley Football Conference]] (MVFC) school to win against a [[Big Ten Conference]] member.{{cn|date=May 2019}} In 2007, the Salukis were victorious against [[Northern Illinois University]].  This marked the second consecutive year that SIU had beaten an [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] program.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=272512459|title=S. Illinois 34, N. Illinois 31|date=September 8, 2007|accessdate=January 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s, SIU set then-MVFC records with 99 consecutive weeks ranked in the top-25 and 14-straight MVFC wins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daily-chronicle.com/articles/2007/09/08/sports/sports03.txt|title=SIU becoming powerhouse at I-AA level|author=|date=|website=daily-chronicle.com|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Conference affiliations==\n* Independent (1913\u20131924, 1962\u20131976)\n* [[Interstate Intercollegiate Athletic Conference]] (1925\u20131961) \n* [[Missouri Valley Conference]] (1977\u20131984)\n* [[Missouri Valley Football Conference]] (1985\u2013present) (known as the Gateway Football Conference until June 2008)\n\n== Postseason games ==\nThe Salukis have appeared in two [[bowl games]], compiling a 2\u20130 record.\n===Bowl games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Southern Illinois Salukis|Season|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| {{cfb link|year=1947|team=Southern Illinois Salukis|title=1947}} || Corn Bowl || [[North Central College|North Central]] || '''W''' 21\u20130\n|-\n| {{cfb link|year=1949|team=Southern Illinois Salukis|title=1949}} || [[Shrine Bowl]] || {{cfb link|year=1949|team=Indiana State Sycamores|title=Indiana State}} || '''W''' 21\u20130\n|}\n\n===Division I-AA/FCS playoffs===\nThe Salukis have appeared in 15 playoff games in I-AA/FCS tournaments, compiling a record of 8\u20137. They won the I-AA national championship in 1983.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Southern Illinois Salukis|Year|Round|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3 bgcolor=lightyellow|[[1983 NCAA Division I-AA football season|1983]] || Quarterfinals || Indiana State || '''W''' 23\u20137\n|-\n| Semifinals ||  Nevada || '''W''' 23\u20137\n|-\n| [[1983 NCAA Division I-AA football season|National Championship Game]] || Western Carolina || '''W''' 43\u20137\n|-\n| [[2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season|2003]] || First Round || Delaware || L 7\u201348\n|-\n| [[2004 NCAA Division I-AA football season|2004]] || First Round || Eastern Washington || L 31\u201335\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2005 NCAA Division I-AA football season|2005]] || First Round || Eastern Illinois || '''W''' 21\u20136\n|-\n| Quarterfinals || Appalachian State || L 24\u201338\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2006 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2006]] || First Round || UT Martin || '''W''' 36\u201330\n|-\n| Quarterfinals || Montana || L 3\u201320\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[2007 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2007]] || First Round || Eastern Illinois || '''W''' 30\u201311\n|-\n| Quarterfinals || UMass || '''W''' 34\u201327\n|-\n| Semifinals ||  Delaware || L 17\u201320\n|-\n| [[2008 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2008]] || First Round || New Hampshire || L 20\u201329\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2009 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2009]] || First Round || Eastern Illinois || '''W''' 48\u20137\n|-\n| Quarterfinals || William & Mary || L 3\u201324\n|}\n\n== Championships ==\n=== Conference championships ===\n* 1947 \u2013 [[Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference Champions]]\n* 1960 \u2013 Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference Co-Champions\n* 1961 \u2013 Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference Champions\n* 2003 \u2013 [[Gateway Football Conference|Gateway Football Conference Co-Champions]]\n* 2004 \u2013 Gateway Football Conference Champions\n* 2005 \u2013 Gateway Football Conference Co-Champions\n* 2008 \u2013 [[Missouri Valley Football Conference|Missouri Valley Football Conference Co-Champions]]\n* 2009 \u2013 Missouri Valley Football Conference Champions\n\n=== National championships ===\n* 1983 \u2013 [[NCAA Division I Football Championship|NCAA Division I-AA Champions]], 43\u20137 win over [[Western Carolina Catamounts football|Western Carolina]]\n\n== Players ==\n=== Salukis in the NFL ===\nSIU has had 28 players drafted in the NFL Draft, including four since 2010. In total, 36 Saluki football players have gone on to play in the NFL. Some notable Salukis in the NFL are listed below.\n\n* [[Kenneth Boatright]]  \u2013 [[Dallas Cowboys]], DE (2013\u20132015)\n* [[Brandon Jacobs]] \u2013 [[New York Giants]], RB (2005\u20132013)\n* [[Bart Scott]]  \u2013 [[New York Jets]], LB (2002\u20132012)\n* [[Carl Mauck]]  \u2013 [[San Diego Chargers]], OL (1969\u20131981, coach 1982\u20132007)\n* [[Damon Jones (American football)|Damon Jones]]  \u2013 [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], TE (1997\u20132001)\n* [[Deji Karim]] \u2013 [[Houston Texans]], RB (2010\u20132014)\n* [[Houston Antwine]]  \u2013 [[Tennessee Titans|Houston OIlers]], DT (1961\u20131972)\n* [[Jayson DiManche]] \u2013 [[Cincinnati Bengals]], LB (2013\u20132017)\n* [[Jewel Hampton]] \u2013 [[San Francisco 49ers]], RB (2012\u20132016)\n* [[Jim Hart (American football)|Jim Hart]]  \u2013 [[Arizona Cardinals|St. Louis Cardinals]], QB (1966\u20131984)\n* [[Kevin House]]  \u2013 [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], WR (1980\u20131987)\n* [[MyCole Pruitt]]  \u2013 [[Minnesota Vikings]], TE (2015\u20132017)\n* [[Sebron Spivey]]  \u2013 [[Dallas Cowboys]], WR (1987)\n* [[Amos Bullocks]]  \u2013 [[Dallas Cowboys]], RB (1962\u20131964)\n* [[Ray Agnew III]]  \u2013 [[Cleveland Browns]], FB (2014\u20132015)\n* [[Terry Taylor (American football)|Terry Taylor]]  \u2013 [[Seattle Seahawks]], DB (1984\u20131995)\n* [[Tom Baugh]] \u2013 [[Kansas City Chiefs]], OL (1986\u20131989)\n* [[Yonel Jourdain]] \u2013 [[Buffalo Bills]], KR, RB (1994\u20131997) \n* [[Korey Lindsey]] \u2013 [[Indianapolis Colts]] & [[Dallas Cowboys]], CB (2012, 2014)\n* [[Chase Allen]] \u2013 [[Miami Dolphins]], LB (2017\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/2975680/chase-allen|title=Chase Allen|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref>\n\n=== All-Americans ===\n[[Cornell Craig]] is the school's all-time leading receiver and first receiver in school history to earn consensus All-American honors (1999).  His senior season he led the nation in receiving with 77 receptions for 1,419 yards and 15 touchdowns.  He also amassed over 2,000 all-purpose yards as a senior.  His career numbers (all Saluki records) are 207 receptions, 3,508 yards, and 37 touchdowns.  He was inducted into the SIU Athletic Hall of Fame in 2008 and is also honored on [[Missouri Valley Conference]]'s 25th anniversary team along with three other Salukis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpsdlocal6.com/sports/local/68993137.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718121751/http://www.wpsdlocal6.com/sports/local/68993137.html |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\n== Home venue ==\n{{main|Saluki Stadium}}\nSIU Football plays at the 15,000-seat [[Saluki Stadium]], which replaced [[McAndrew Stadium]], the home of Saluki Football since 1938.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nelson|first=Kathleen|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|url=http://www.stltoday.com/sports/other/article_3a3fdb86-fea7-514d-a467-139c0f8aed04.html|title=SIUC's long-awaited new stadium is ready|date=August 23, 2010|accessdate=January 12, 2011}}</ref> Saluki Stadium opened on September 2, 2010 when a sellout crowd of 15,200 watched the Salukis defeat [[Quincy University|Quincy]] 70\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://siusalukis.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/090210aae.html|title=Saluki Stadium opens in grand fashion - Southern Illinois University|author=|date=|website=Southern Illinois University|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Saluki Stadium is part of the university's larger athletic facilities plan, known as \"Saluki Way,\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Norris|first=D.W.|work=[[The Southern Illinoisan]]|url=http://www.thesouthern.com/lifestyles/magazine/article_a1b25ed8-9378-11df-8457-001cc4c002e0.html|title=How 'Suite' it is: New Saluki football stadium scores with premium seating level|date=July 24, 2010|accessdate=January 12, 2011}}</ref> a comprehensive plan to renovate and restructure the campus athletic facilities.<ref>[http://www.siuc.edu/future/salukiWay/index.html  Saluki Way] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100228222345/http://www.siuc.edu/future/salukiWay/index.html |date=2010-02-28 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Southern Illinois Salukis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://siusalukis.com/sports/m-footbl/silu-m-footbl-body.html}}\n\n{{Southern Illinois Salukis football navbox}}\n{{Southern Illinois University}}\n{{Missouri Valley Football Conference navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Southern Illinois Salukis football|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName         = Southern Illinois Salukis football\n| CurrentSeason    = 2020 Southern Illinois Salukis football team\n| Image            = Southern Illinois Salukis logo.svg\n| ImageSize        = 250\n| HeadCoach        = [[Nick Hill]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 3rd\n| HCWins           = 10 <!-- As of g